# Northbound Treatment — SEO Infrastructure

## Core Invariants — Never Break These

### 1. All page metadata must be dynamic
Every `src/app/**/page.tsx` in `apps/northbound-treatment` must use `generateMetadata` + `resolveTrackedPageMetadata`.
**Never** use `export const metadata: Metadata = {...}` on a page (static exports bake metadata at build time, making admin-panel SEO edits invisible without a redeploy).

✅ Correct pattern:
```tsx
import { resolveTrackedPageMetadata } from "@sweetmedia/admin-core";

const fallback: Metadata = {
  title: "Page Title | Northbound Treatment",
  description: "...",
  alternates: { canonical: "/route-path" },
};

export async function generateMetadata(): Promise<Metadata> {
  return resolveTrackedPageMetadata("/route-path", fallback);
}
```

❌ Never do this on a page file:
```tsx
export const metadata: Metadata = { title: "...", description: "..." };
```

### 2. Every page fallback must include a canonical URL
`alternates: { canonical: "/exact-route-path" }` is required in every fallback object.

### 3. The revalidation route must exist and be called after any admin metadata save
`apps/northbound-treatment/src/app/api/admin/revalidate/route.ts` calls `revalidatePath()` and must not be deleted or modified to remove that call. Admin-core calls this endpoint after applying SEO changes — preserving that call chain is mandatory.

### 4. Do not add `force-dynamic` or remove `revalidate` from blog routes
The blog index and blog post routes use ISR. Do not change their caching strategy without explicit instruction.

### 5. robots.ts must remain dynamic
`src/app/robots.ts` generates the robots config dynamically. Do not replace it with a static `robots.txt` file.
